						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">Canite wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">And in the example code you gave, 3gengames, would I have to do this?<br /><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">ReadyLoop:<br />LDA Frame<br />JMP Loop ; jump to Loop? or will it go there automatically?<br />Loop:<br />CMP Frame<br />BNE Loop<br />JMP ReadyLoop<br />;blah blah</div><br />Otherwise, where am I supposed to jump to the Loop?</div><br />A label is just a line in the program that has a name. You don't need to JMP to a label that's the next line; instead, the CPU is said to "fall through" once it crosses the label. If you know any C or PHP, "falling through" it's like the behavior of a switch statement when you don't break. Sometimes, entire subroutines will "fall through" to other subroutines as part of a tail call.<br /><br />For one thing, I think that's supposed to be a BEQ, not a BNE, as you want it stuck in the loop while the frame count is equal (that is, until it changes).<br /><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">ReadyLoop:<br />&nbsp; LDA Frame<br />Loop:<br />&nbsp; CMP Frame<br />&nbsp; BEQ Loop<br /><br />&nbsp; JMP ReadyLoop<br />;blah blah</div></div>

